  "prompt": "Can non-profit organizations pay a salary?",
  "response": "Yes, non-profit organizations can and do pay salaries to their employees, including executives and staff. Here are some key points:\n\n1. Compensation is allowed\n- Non-profits can pay reasonable salaries\n- Employees receive wages like in for-profit businesses\n- Salaries must be competitive but not excessive\n\n2. Legal requirements\n- Salaries must be appropriate for the role and organization size\n- Compensation should be comparable to similar positions in the sector\n- Must comply with minimum wage and labor laws\n\n3. Board oversight\n- The board of directors typically approves salary structures\n- Ensures compensation is reasonable and aligned with organizational mission\n\n4. Funding sources\n- Salaries can be paid from:\n  - Donations\n  - Grants\n  - Program revenue\n  - Fundraising activities\n\n5. Restrictions\n- Executive compensation must not be unreasonably high\n- IRS monitors excessive compensation in non-profits\n- Large salaries can jeopardize tax-exempt status\n\n6. Transparency\n- Many non-profits must disclose salary information on tax forms\n- Promotes accountability and public trust\n\nWhile non-profits can pay salaries, the primary focus remains on the organization's mission rather than profit generation.",
